Some teachers' unions in KZN are advising their members not to report for duty tomorrow. The five unions include Sadtu and Naptosa. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The Kwazulu-Natal education department has refuted claims by unions that schools aren't ready to operate. Five unions, which include Sadtu and Naptosa, have advised their members not to show up for work on Thursday. They say government has failed to prepare schools to reopen properly amid the COVID-19 outbreak. READ: Parents worried about safety of children at schools: online survey The unions claim few water tanks have been installed at poor and rural schools, so no water could be delivered to them. They also claim government has not adequately consulted with them. READ: Union to take govt to court over schools reopening Education MEC Kwazi Mshengu says unions were consulted on a number of issues. "I've read the statement and it's unfortunate," Mshengu said. "They know some of the things they alleging are not true." - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.